<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="190" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1539,2032]" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1539,1564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The species is charaterized by the simple mandibular margin combined with the appressed setae on the frons. The gaster is black or partly red. The clypeal lobe is enlarged, with rounded apex, and laterally convex. For further description see 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulawski" box="[408,595,1611,1636]" pageId="3" pageNumber="190" refString="Pulawski, W. J. (1992) World Species of the Wasp Genus Holotachysphex de Beaumont (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 94, 223 - 242." type="journal article" year="1992">Pulawski (1992)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1539,2032]" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,408,1647,1672]" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">Color variability.</emphasis>
The male and female from 
<collectingCountry box="[739,819,1647,1672]" name="Turkey" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">Turkey</collectingCountry>
have a completely black abdomen and black femora (tibae and tarsi partly reddish, sternum II with some reddish shimmer, apical tergal bands transparent), whereas both males from 
<collectingCountry box="[342,417,1719,1744]" name="Jordan" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">Jordan</collectingCountry>
have abdominal segments Iâ€“II (Iâ€“III), parts of fore- and midfemora, all hindfemora, tibiae and tarsi light red. Both forms are the same structurally. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulawski" box="[790,975,1755,1780]" pageId="3" pageNumber="190" refString="Pulawski, W. J. (1992) World Species of the Wasp Genus Holotachysphex de Beaumont (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 94, 223 - 242." type="journal article" year="1992">Pulawski (1992)</bibRefCitation>
mentions only red coloured females and the males he examined were all black. However, there is no evidence that the color forms are different species, and the red form is probably only a variation of 
<taxonomicName box="[641,752,1827,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Tachysphex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mochii">
<emphasis box="[641,752,1827,1851]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="190">H. mochii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
